mber 1381","1320":"1320","before 1351":"before 1351","1351":"1351","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","before March 1381":"before March 1381","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","Harbottle, Northumberland, England":"Harbottle, Northumberland, England","Crawcrook, Durham, England":"Crawcrook, Durham, England","England":"England","Togston, Northumberland, England":"Togston, Northumberland, England","Farnham, Northumberland, England":"Farnham, Northumberland, England","Alwinton, Northumberland, England":"Alwinton, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Horsley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northeastern England): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>hors</i> ‘horse’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, such as Horsley (Derbyshire, Gloucestershire), Long Horsley (Northumberland), and Horseley Hills Farm in Wolverley (Worcestershire), probably referring to a place where horses were put out to pasture."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":31,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Horsley was born before 1351 as the son of Richard Horsley. He married Joan Strother before March 1381. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He lived in Farnham, Northumberland, England in 1391 and Crawcrook, Durham, England in 1391. He registered for military service in 1391. He died on 2 November 1391, in England."},"et":{"before 1351–2 November 1391":"enne 1351–2. november 1391","1351–1391":"1351–1391","1351–Male":"1351–Surnud","–1412":"–1412","–Female":"Surnud","1381–1444":"1381–1444","1320–1372":"1320–1372","2 November 1391":"2. november 1391","1412":"1412","1444":"1444","30 November 1381":"30. november 1381","1320":"1320","before 1351":"enne 1351","1351":"1351","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","before March 1381":"enne märtsi 1381","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","Harbottle, Northumberland, England":"Harbottle, Northumberland, England","Crawcrook, Durham, England":"Crawcrook, Durham, England","England":"England","Togston, Northumberland, England":"Togston, Northumberland, England","Farnham, Northumberland, England":"Farnham, Northumberland, England","Alwinton, Northumberland, England":"Alwinton, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"before 1351–2 November 1391":"ennen vuotta 1351–2. marraskuuta 1391","1351–1391":"1351–1391","1351–Male":"1351–Kuollut","–1412":"–1412","–Female":"Kuollut","1381–1444":"1381–1444","1320–1372":"1320–1372","2 November 1391":"2. marraskuuta 1391","1412":"1412","1444":"1444","30 November 1381":"30. marraskuuta 1